1601006400.title: Bargain Hunt
1601006400.descr: Two teams of amateur antique collectors meet at an antiques fair to compete to make the largest profit from a three hundred pound budget. Once the contestants have done the shopping for their own items, the experts then take any leftover money and go shopping for more antiques which is 'bonus buys'. The teams then have to decide whether or not to take these items to auction.

1601009100.title: Bargain Hunt
1601009100.descr: The Welsh capital, Cardiff, plays host to today's Bargain Hunt. With Christina Trevanion at the helm, the teams head to Jacobs Market to bag a bargain in the hope that they will make a profit at auction.

1601011800.title: Last of the Summer Wine
1601011800.descr: Clegg is writing his memoirs, but is having trouble remembering people's names; Clegg, Truly and Billy meet a man who wants to sail to Ilkley in an inflatable swan, unfortunately it has developed a puncture which Entwistle repairs; Clegg climbs a tree so he can see the church clock, unfortunately he gets stuck; Tom and Entwistle try to cheer Smiler up after he has been dumped by Hermione.

1601013600.title: Call the Midwife
1601013600.descr: Period drama series set in East London in the 1950s, following the life and work of a young midwife Jenny Lee and her colleagues at the Nonnatus House nursing convent. They serve the poor society of Poplar, London. Their main duty is to help bring safe birth to women and help them look after their newborns.

1601016900.title: Impossible
1601016900.descr: Entertaining and educational British quiz show, hosted by Rick Edwards, where 24 regular contestants compete throughout the series to answer tricky questions. But some of the optional answers are designed to be ''impossible'', or at the very least inconsistent with the information given. The participants must avoid selecting these booby trap answer and the best one wins the £10,000 jackpot.

1601025000.title: Father Brown
1601025000.descr: Father Brown is a Catholic priest and an amateur detective solving murder cases, set during the 1950s in the fictional village Kembleford in Cotswold area, England. He uses his own wits as well as skills of his close friends, and being a priest allows him to look straight to the truth. He is strongly against the capital punishment for the capital crimes, as still applied in Britain of that time.

1601055000.title: Father Brown
1601055000.descr: Mark Williams, James Dreyfus, Martin Docherty, Tom Chambers, Anna-Louise Plowman, Sorcha Cusack. Drama series based on the novels of GK Chesterton. Father Brown becomes embroiled in an audacious art heist masterminded by his adversary Flambeau, who intends to use the priest and his friends to help him settle an old score.

1601057700.title: Doctor Who
1601057700.descr: London, 1814. The entire city has turned out for the biggest Frost Fair in decades! But beneath the frozen Thames, revellers are disappearing, snatched through the ice. Pulled into the depths where a terrifying monster lurks. Will the Doctor and Bill stop the slaughter before they too are dragged into the icy waters?

1601060400.title: Shirley
1601060400.descr: A biopic of Shirley Bassey, charting her early career from her humble roots in 1930s Wales to her rise to stardom in the 1960s.

1601064600.title: Josh
1601064600.descr: Josh Widdlecombe's (comedian) fun loving comedy on living in North London, and the laughs you can have when living with your two best friends. Kate, Owen and Josh share awkward and laughable adult moments in the sitcom, some including their weird landlord, Geoff.

1601066100.title: W1A
1601066100.descr: Following on from the BAFTA award-winning Twenty Twelve: the BBC has a new Head of Values, Ian Fletcher and he's been given the huge task of sorting the corporation out, he has to "restructure" it. The BBC is becoming under a huge load of pressure with the content that they produce. This British comedy is the BBC realising where it goes wrong and is essentially criticising itself.

1601067900.title: Live at the Apollo
1601067900.descr: Hammersmith Apollo Theatre hosts some of the biggest names in stand up comedy. Hosted by Jack Dee, performing his own sketches and introducing well known and loved acts such as Lee Mack, Michael McIntyre, Sean Lock and Sarah Millican. Running since September 2004, this showtime series is a classic comedy staple, drawing crowds in their staggering numbers to the theatre in West London, every year.
